Get twitter API data¶

In [18]:
consumer_key = 'removed'
consumer_secret = 'removed'
access_token = 'removed'
access_token_secret = 'removed'

auth = tweepy.OAuthHandler(consumer_key, consumer_secret)
auth.set_access_token(access_token, access_token_secret)

api = tweepy.API(auth, wait_on_rate_limit=True, wait_on_rate_limit_notify=True)

Caution! Cell below took 28min to run the first time¶

In [47]:
#get all the tweet JSONs into a list

listOfTweetJSONs = []
listOfFailedTweetIDs = []
startOfLoop = time.time()

for i in range(tweetArchive.shape[0]):
    curTweetID = str(tweetArchive.iloc[i, 0])
    startOfThisLoop = time.time()
    
    print(str(i) + ": getting tweet_id " + curTweetID)
    print("    current time: ", startOfThisLoop)
    
    try:
        listOfTweetJSONs.append(api.get_status(curTweetID, tweet_mode='extended'))
    except:
        listOfFailedTweetIDs.append(curTweetID)
    
    print("    request took (in seconds): ", time.time()-startOfThisLoop)
    

print('----------------')
print('Total time taken (secs): ', time.time()-startOfLoop)

#summarise the different types of values
dogCatagoryColNames = ['doggo', 'floofer', 'pupper', 'puppo']

def countNotNones(row):
    x = 0
    for i in dogCatagoryColNames:
        if row[i] != 'None':
            x += 1
    return x


tweetArchive[dogCatagoryColNames].apply(countNotNones, axis=1).value_counts()
Out[240]:
0    1976
1     366
2      14
dtype: int64

A majority of dogs don't get identified as 'doggo', 'floofer', 'pupper' or 'puppo', only 366 as one and 14 as two of them.

Unsure how to handle the rows with two dog types. Will look at them closer.

Cleaning Issues¶

tweetArchive dataframe¶

  • source column is html tags instead of just the hyperlink (not correcting as won't be used in analysis)
  • rows with any values in the retweeted_status... columns can be dropped. Only original tweets wanted.
    • those columns can then be dropped
  • timestamp column isn't datetime data type
  • tweet_id is an int, should be a string as just an id
  • some rating_numerator values wrong when there's a decimal in the numerator. Misses bit before decimal eg 786709082849828864 read as 75/10 instead of 9.75/10 and 883482846933004288 should be 13.5/10 instead of 5/10
    • change data type of rating_numerator column to float to allow this
  • many outlying values in for rating_numerator and rating_denominator. Reviewed visually.
    • 716439118184652801 50/50 should be 11/10
    • 666287406224695296 should be 9/10 not 1/2
    • remove all ratings of 6 and below. Very rarely dogs, just joke stuff like an electric fan or a sheep.
  • some rows are replies to other tweets. Not needed. Remove any rows with values in in_reply_to_status_id
    • Then drop the in_reply_to_status_id and in_reply_to_user_id columns.

twitterAPIdf dataframe¶

  • id column should be string instead of int
  • id column is named differently to other two dataframes where it's tweet_id
  • drop all rows with favorite_count of zero. They're just retweets.
  • only keep favorite_count, retweet_count and id columns

tweetBreedPredictions dataframe¶

  • tweet_id should be string
  • rename all other columns to be more descriptive eg img_num to img_num_with_highest_prediction, p1 to most_likely_breed

Tidiness Issues¶

tweetArchive¶

  • columns for doggo, floofer, pupper, puppo have values of None or the column heading repeated as the row's value.
    • A lot of cases where no dog type is identified
    • A handful of cases where two dog types are identified

tweetArchive and twitterAPIdf¶

  • merge twitterAPIdf into tweetArchive to include favorite_count and retweet_count

tweetArchive and tweetBreedPredictions¶

  • merge tweetBreedPredictions into tweetArchive to include the most likely dog prediction

tweetBreedPredictions¶

  • melt prediction columns to have one column for is_a_dog_or_not, prediction_confidence, rank (not correcting as won't be used in analysis).

End Assessing Step¶

In [274]:
#create a function for this regex
def numeratorUpdate(row):
    #need to cast row.rating_numerator as int as I just changed it's data type to float
    #strings would come up as '75.0' otherwise
    pattern = r'(\d+\.' + str(int(row.rating_numerator)) + r')/' + str(row.rating_denominator)
    searchObj = re.search(pattern, row.text)
    
    if searchObj:
        #if it found a match then return the first group, as opposed to
        #group(0) which would be the whole match
        return float(searchObj.group(1))
    else:
        return np.nan

Tidiness Issue #1¶

tweetArchive dataframe

  • columns for doggo, floofer, pupper, puppo have values of None or the column heading repeated as the row's value.
    • A lot of cases where no dog type is identified
    • A handful of cases where two dog types are identified

Define¶

  • Combine into one column with catagorical variables for the dog types.
  • Where no the values are "None" for all catagories give value NaN
  • Where there's more than one value concatenate with and eg "doggo and floofer"

Code¶

In [322]:
def dog_age_stage_combiner(row):
    dogStageCols = ['doggo', 'floofer', 'pupper', 'puppo']
    combinedDogStage = ''
    
    for i in range(len(dogStageCols)):
        x = row[dogStageCols[i]]
        if x != 'None':
            #capitalizing it just so it looks better in plots later
            combinedDogStage += x.capitalize() + ' and '
    
    if combinedDogStage: #strings are true if they're not blank
        return  combinedDogStage[:-5] #strip ' and ' off end
    else:
        return  np.nan

Re-Define¶

Looking at the tweetBreedPredictions table again I realise it would be best to combine the most_likely_breed and most_likely_breed_is_dog columns to create a new single column that has either a dog breed prediciton or NaN.

In the analysis I plan to do I want to look at the most common breeds of dogs so don't can about any non dogs.

This adds another a cleaning item to this step:

  • combine most_likely_breed and most_likely_breed_is_dog columns into a most_likely_dog_breed column that only has dog breeds and NaNs for non dog predictions.
  • merge tweetBreedPredictions into tweetArchive to include most_likely_dog_breed

In [358]:
def onlyDogBreeds(row):
    if row.most_likely_breed_is_dog:
        return row.most_likely_breed
    else:
        return np.nan

tweetBreedPredictions_clean['most_likely_dog_breed'] = tweetBreedPredictions_clean.apply(onlyDogBreeds, axis=1)

Insight #1: Average Rating¶

The first thing I want to look at is what is the average rating?

I'm normalising the values by diving by the denominator and then multiplying again by 10 to deal with the few values that have a very high numerator and high denominator.

In [480]:
analysisDf['normRatings'] = ((analysisDf.rating_numerator / analysisDf.rating_denominator)*10)
In [481]:
print('Mean:', analysisDf.normRatings.mean())
print('Median:', analysisDf.normRatings.median())
print('Mode:', analysisDf.normRatings.mode())

Mean: 12.06598385469223
Median: 11.0
Mode: 0    12.0
dtype: float64

The average value is 12/10 but interestingly the median is lower at 11/10. This suggests the distribution is skewed I'm interested to plot what it is.

Visualisation #1: Normalised Ratings Distribution¶

In [551]:
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6)) #set plot size, must do before calling .plot()

analysisDf.normRatings.hist(bins = 8, range=(7,15), align='left')

plt.title('Ratings out of 10 distribution')
plt.xlabel('Rating')
plt.ylabel('Frequency')
plt.show()

This shows a negatively skewed distribution.

As shown by the mode 12 is indeed the most common rating closely followed by 10 and then 11. There's a few lucky dogs who manage 14.

In [483]:
(analysisDf.normRatings[analysisDf.normRatings>=14].count() / analysisDf.normRatings.count()) *100
Out[483]:
2.0686175580221997

They really are lucky dogs. Only 2.1% of dogs manage a rating of 14 or more!

Insight/Visualisation #2: Ratings over time¶

I'm interested to look at this as you hear a lot about grade inflation in the education system. Does the same apply to the world of social media based cute dog rating?

In [533]:
meanRatingsWithTime = analysisDf.normRatings.groupby([analysisDf.timestamp.dt.year, analysisDf.timestamp.dt.month]).mean()
In [552]:
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6)) #set plot size, must do before calling .plot()

meanRatingsWithTime.plot()

plt.xlabel('Date (Year, month number)')
plt.ylabel('Mean Rating Out of 10')
plt.title('Mean Ratings with Time')
plt.show()

Whoa! What's going on in mid-ish 2016!

But also Whoa! Ratings are definetly increasing with time! No one is immue from grade inflation it seems, not even revered dog raters.

Look at those figures! The mean rating per month has increased from roughly 10.5/10 at the start of 2016 to an increadible 13/10 by August 2017.

I'm going to take a look at what's causing the outlier in July 2016.

In [513]:
analysisDf[(analysisDf.timestamp >= '2016-07') & (analysisDf.timestamp < '2016-08')].rating_numerator.value_counts()
Out[513]:

In [523]:
analysisDf[analysisDf.rating_numerator == 1776].text.iloc[0]
Out[523]:
"This is Atticus. He's quite simply America af. 1776/10 https://t.co/GRXwMxLBkh"

The high value was for a very high rating of 1776/10 given to one dog that is skewing the mean. I could remove that value but don't want to seeing as it's a real rating.

One way to avoid this skewing in the plot would be to take the median instead of the mean. This will be less skewed by high values.

In [553]:
medianRatingsWithTime = analysisDf.normRatings.groupby([analysisDf.timestamp.dt.year, analysisDf.timestamp.dt.month]).median()

plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
medianRatingsWithTime.plot()
plt.title('Median Ratings with Time')
plt.xlabel('Date (Year, month number)')
plt.ylabel('Median Rating Out of 10')
plt.show()

This makes the increase with time even clearer. It's now also blockier as median value each month is a whole number.

You can really see the walk from 10 to 13.
